Oncology dataset analysis summary for ds001_nsclc

I analyzed 50000 NSCLC patient records with no missing values in the decoded Parquet file. The outcome was pfs_months, modeled as a continuous endpoint. Analyses used unadjusted mean comparisons for direct subgroup contrasts and ordinary least-squares models for multivariable main-effect and interaction tests; signed estimates are in months of progression-free survival.

Main treatment and biomarker findings

- Iteration 1 tested unadjusted treatment main effects. Pembrolizumab, sotorasib, and osimertinib were positive; olaparib was slightly negative before biomarker stratification.
- Iteration 2 evaluated immunotherapy biomarkers. Both PD-L1 TPS and TMB-high had positive adjusted associations with PFS.
- Iteration 3 refined immunotherapy hypotheses: pembrolizumab benefit rose with PD-L1 and was much larger in TMB-high tumors.
- Iteration 4 found STK11 mutation was adverse overall and specifically reduced pembrolizumab-associated PFS.
- Iteration 5 identified a strong KRAS G12C-specific sotorasib benefit.
- Iteration 6 suggested STK11 mutation blunted sotorasib benefit in KRAS G12C disease.
- Iteration 7 found a strong EGFR-specific osimertinib benefit.
- Iteration 8 showed brain metastases did not erase osimertinib benefit; the subgroup contrast was small to modest.
- Iteration 9 found a large BRCA2-specific olaparib benefit despite no favorable unselected main effect.

Other driver biomarker findings

- Iteration 10 screened other actionable fusions; ALK and ROS1 were favorable prognostic markers.
- Iteration 11 found MET exon14 and HER2 amplification were not favorable; MET was clearly adverse, HER2 weaker.

Clinical and laboratory prognostic findings

- Iteration 12 showed RET fusion was favorable, while the EGFR main effect was not independently favorable once osimertinib use and covariates were included.
- Iteration 13 confirmed ECOG performance status and stage IV disease as adverse clinical factors.
- Iteration 14 found brain and liver metastases were both strongly adverse.
- Iteration 15 found bone metastases and recent weight loss were adverse.
- Iteration 16 confirmed albumin was favorable while LDH was adverse.
- Iteration 17 found systemic inflammation markers CRP and NLR were adverse.
- Iteration 18 found squamous histology and current smoking were adverse.
- Iteration 19 found higher hemoglobin was favorable and alkaline phosphatase adverse.

Comorbidity and final interaction findings

- Iteration 20 tested electrolyte signals; sodium was weakly favorable while calcium was adverse.
- Iteration 21 found COPD and chronic kidney disease were adverse comorbidities.
- Iteration 22 tested autoimmune disease as an immunotherapy modifier; the interaction was small and not convincingly significant.
- Iteration 23 found interstitial lung disease and heart failure had adverse adjusted associations.
- Iteration 24 verified the PD-L1 interaction using a cohort-median TPS cut point; the high-PD-L1 interaction was positive.
- Iteration 25 pooled the targeted therapy pattern: matched biomarker-directed therapy was strongly associated with longer PFS.

Overall conclusion

The strongest supported patterns were treatment-by-biomarker relationships. Pembrolizumab was most favorable in tumors with higher PD-L1 TPS and TMB-high status, but STK11 mutation was adverse and reduced pembrolizumab-associated benefit. Sotorasib showed a strong KRAS G12C-specific benefit, olaparib showed a strong BRCA2-specific benefit, and osimertinib showed a strong EGFR-specific benefit. A pooled matched-targeted-therapy analysis across EGFR, KRAS G12C, and BRCA2-positive patients supported the same overall conclusion: biomarker-matched therapy was associated with materially longer PFS. Clinical severity, metastatic burden, inflammation, low albumin, high LDH, weight loss, squamous histology, current smoking, and several comorbidities were adverse prognostic signals.

